    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Prayer Ruling: Helpful or Hurtful?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Herbert Rosenberg letter on June 20 article opposes organized school prayer</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Student Prayers Must Be Private, Court Reaffirms'' (front page, June 20):</p>
        <p>Years ago, when I was a freshman at Brooklyn Technical High School, the practice was that at assembly the students stood and recited ''The Lord's Prayer.'' As a Jew, I stood, but remained silent. My silence was noticed, and after assembly some students beat me up. I left Brooklyn Tech after one semester.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Student Prayers Must Be Private, Court Reaffirms'' (front page, June 20):</p>
        <p>Years ago, when I was a freshman at Brooklyn Technical High School, the practice was that at assembly the students stood and recited ''The Lord's Prayer.'' As a Jew, I stood, but remained silent. My silence was noticed, and after assembly some students beat me up. I left Brooklyn Tech after one semester.</p>
        <p>Those who believe that coercion is an academic matter should be aware that however much has changed over the years, a teenage high school student who does not conform pays a price -- whether ostracism, name-calling or a beating. That applies especially in matters regarding organized prayer.</p>
        <p>HERBERT ROSENBERG  Dobbs Ferry, N.Y., June 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
